{'title': 'Extreme noise. Problems with water. Poor service. Not recommended.', 'positive': 'On the first day, we were allowed to use the kitchen to make instant noodles.', 'negative': "On the first day, there was a problem with the water (no hot water; brown water coming out of the tap). This was solved a day later, but there was a problem with rain leaking into the room. In addition, fellow guests were making a lot of noise moving furniture around. So the walls and ceilings here are very thin. On the third day, the situation got worse. There was a party next door, with huge speakers, leading to extreme noise the entire evening. The noise was so bad that the windows of our room were literally shaking - it was as if we were sleeping next to an outdoor music festival. The children couldn't sleep, so we asked the reception for a temporary extra room, where we could put the children until the end of the party. They refused to provide this free of charge. Instead, they wanted to move us into two other small rooms, but they demanded that we leave our family room immediately - with all our luggage, at 9.30 pm! When we refused this, the member of staff started calling us on our room phone to argue and became downright hostile. Very poor service. We had no choice but to check out early the next morning. If the city of Bac Lieu doesn't change its regulations about noise pollution (as other Vietnamese cities have done!), and hotel owners here don't learn how to treat customers well, they will not be successful in their ambitions to attract more (international) tourists."}
